    "# The model we want to use\n",
    "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier\n",
    "\n",
    "# How we want to judge if our score is good or not by telling us\n",
    "# what percentage of the time is our model correct\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score\n",
    "\n",
    "# Helps us work with tables of data\n",
    "import numpy as np"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 44,
   "id": "54a665ca",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Start with 5 years of data: 2008 - 2013 = 260 rows\n",
    "START = 260 \n",
    "\n",
    "# Step from 2014 to now(2022)\n",
    "STEP = 52\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a prediction function with params(training_set,test_set,predictors, \n",
    "# and target) to return predictions\n",
    "def predict(train,test,predictors,target):\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Inialize our model:\n",
    "    # min_sample_split: protects from overfitting\n",
    "    # random_state: every time we run our model it will generate the same \n",
    "    # sequence of numbers to give us the same result\n",
    "    rf = RandomForestClassifier(min_samples_split=10,random_state=1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Train our model on our training set\n",
    "    rf.fit(train[predictors],train[target])\n",
    "   \n",
    "    # Test our model on our test set\n",
    "    preds = rf.predict(test[predictors])\n",
    "    return preds\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# How we can avoid using future data to predict the past that cross validation\n",
    "# seems to do\n",
    "def backtest(data,predictors,target):\n",
    "    # append all prediction to an empty list\n",
    "    all_preds = []\n",
    "    # Start from 2008 to 2013 then make predictions for 2014, then it will\n",
    "    # take data from 2008 - 2014 to make prediction for 2015 and etc.\n",
    "    for i in range(START, data.shape[0],STEP):\n",
    "        # Everything up until i\n",
    "        train = price_data.iloc[:i]\n",
    "        # The year following i \n",
    "        test = price_data.iloc[i:(i+STEP)]\n",
    "        # append all predictions\n",
    "        all_preds.append(predict(train,test,predictors,target))\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # concate all numpy arrays and our accuracy intoone array    \n",
    "    preds = np.concatenate(all_preds)\n",
    "    # give us our accuracy score\n",
    "    return preds, accuracy_score(data.iloc[START:][target],preds)\n"
   ]
  },
